'''John Day Fossil Beds National Monument''' is a {{convert|13,944|acre|adj=on}} park in eastern [[Oregon]]. Located within the [[John Day River]] Basin, this [[U.S. National Monument]] is world renowned for its well preserved, remarkably complete record of [[fossil]] plants and animals, a record that spans more than 40 of the 65 million years of the [[Cenozoic Era]] (also known as the Age of [[Mammal]]s and [[Angiosperm|Flowering Plants]]). The monument is divided into three units: [[Painted Hills]] (named for the delicately colored [[Stratigraphy|stratifications]]) northwest of [[Mitchell, Oregon|Mitchell]], Sheep Rock which is northwest of [[Dayville, Oregon|Dayville]], and Clarno which is {{convert|20|mi|km}} west of [[Fossil, Oregon|Fossil]]. Blue Basin is a [[volcanic ash]] bowl transformed into claystone by eons of [[erosion]], colored pastel blue by [[mineral]]s.

Visitors can follow trails into the [[badland]]s and examine fossils displayed at the visitor center while [[scientist]]s continue field investigations and the painstaking analysis of the monument's vast fossil record.  The Sheep Rock unit includes the '''Thomas Condon Paleontology Center''' with exhibits of fossils, and the [[James Cant Ranch Historic District|Cant Ranch Museum]] which serves as the monument's headquarters and includes exhibits about human settlements on the ranch and in the area.  The museums are located 2 miles (3.2 km) miles north of Picture Gorge along Route 19 near [[Dayville, Oregon|Dayville]].

Exploration and study of the John Day fossil beds continues today. In many of the beds, the fossils are widely scattered, and their occurrence cannot be predicted. Many types of fossils deteriorate rapidly once erosion exposes them to the elements. Thus the fossil beds are continually canvassed by paleontologists. Visitors often take rocks as souvenirs, which is a federal crime.<ref>
  {{cite news
  |title = Stolen Treasure: Theft is a problem at Oregon monument
  |first = Kate
  |last = Ramsayer
  |work = Seattle Post-Intelligencer
  |publisher = The Bend Bulletin
  |url = http://www.seattlepi.com/getaways/344032_fossils20.html
  |date=December 19, 2007 }}</ref>

The fossil beds contain vestiges of the actual soils, rivers, ponds, watering holes, mudslides, ashfalls, [[floodplain]]s, [[midden]]s, [[fossil trackway|trackway]]s, [[prairie]]s, and forests, in an unbroken sequence that is one of the longest continuous geological records. The rocks are rich with the evidence of ancient habitats and the dynamic processes that shaped them; they tell of sweeping changes in the John Day Basin. Great changes, too, have taken place in this area's landscape, climate, and in the kinds of plants and animals that have inhabited it.

==Geography==

The John Day Fossil Beds National Monument consists of three widely separated units<U+2014>Sheep Rock, Painted Hills, and Clarno<U+2014>in the [[John Day River]] basin of east-central Oregon. Located in rugged terrain in the counties of [[Wheeler County, Oregon|Wheeler]] and [[Grant County, Oregon|Grant]], the park units are characterized by hills, deep ravines, and eroded fossil-bearing rock formations.<ref name ="Nature and Science">{{cite web|title=Nature and Science|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/index.htm|date=September 24, 2006|accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>  To the west lies the [[Cascade Range]], to the south the [[Ochoco Mountains]], and to the east the [[Blue Mountains (Oregon)|Blue Mountains]].<ref name="DeLorme"/> Elevations within the {{convert|13944|acre|ha|lk=on|adj=on}}<ref name="red book">{{cite book|title=The National Parks Index 2009<U+2013>2011|publisher= National Park Service|year =2009|format=PDF|url = http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/nps/index2009_11.pdf|page=73|ISBN=978-0-912627-81-6|accessdate = July 8, 2011}}</ref> park range from {{convert|2000|to|4500|ft|m}}.<ref name ="Nature and Science"/>

The Clarno Unit, the westernmost of the three units, consists of {{convert|1969|acre|ha}} located {{convert|18|mi|km}} west of [[Fossil, Oregon|Fossil]] along [[Oregon Route 218]].<ref name="NPS Clarno">{{cite web|title= Clarno Unit|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/clarno_unit.htm|publisher = National Park Service|date=July 25, 2006|accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> The Painted Hills Unit, which lies about halfway between the other two units, covers {{convert|3132|acre|ha}}.<ref name="NPS Painted Hills">{{cite web|title= Painted Hills Unit|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/painted_hills_unit.htm|publisher = National Park Service|date=July 25, 2006|accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> It is situated about {{convert|9|mi|km}} northwest of [[Mitchell, Oregon|Mitchell]] along Burnt Ranch Road, which intersects [[U.S. Route 26 in Oregon|U.S. Route 26]] west of Mitchell.<ref name="DeLorme"/> The remaining {{convert|8843|acre|ha}}{{#tag:ref|Derived by subtracting the sizes of the Clarno and Painted Hills units from the total area of the park.|group=n}} of the park, the Sheep Rock Unit, are located along [[Oregon Route 19]] and the John Day River upstream of the [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] community of [[Kimberly, Oregon|Kimberly]].<ref name="DeLorme"/> The Sheep Rock Unit is further subdivided into the Mascall Formation Overlook, Picture Gorge, the [[James Cant Ranch Historic District]], Cathedral Rock, Blue Basin, and the Foree Area, some of which are separated from one another by farms and ranches and other parcels of land that are not part of the park.<ref name="NPS Sheep Rock Trails">{{cite web|title= Sheep Rock Trails|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/sheep-rock-trails.htm|publisher = National Park Service|date=June 21, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref>  

By highway, the park headquarters, the main visitor center, and the Cant Ranch<U+2014>all part of the Sheep Rock Unit<U+2014>are {{convert|9|mi|km}} west of Dayville,<ref name="Accessibility"/> {{convert|41|mi|km}} west of the city of [[John Day, Oregon|John Day]], {{convert|80|mi|km}} east of [[Prineville, Oregon|Prineville]], {{convert|122|mi|km}} northeast of [[Bend, Oregon|Bend]], and {{convert|240|mi|km}} southeast of [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]].<ref name="NPS Travel Tips">{{cite web|title= Traffic & Travel Tips|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/trafficandtraveltips.htm|publisher = National Park Service|date=July 25, 2006|accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> The shortest highway distances from unit to unit within the park are Sheep Rock to Painted Hills, {{convert|45|mi|km}}; Painted Hills to Clarno, {{convert|75|mi|km}}, and Clarno to Sheep Rock, {{convert|81|mi|km}}.<ref name="DeLorme">{{cite book|title= Oregon Atlas & Gazetter|edition=7th|publisher=DeLorme|location=Yarmouth, Maine|year=2008|pages=76<U+2013>77|isbn=978-0-89933-347-2}}</ref><ref name="NPS Travel Tips"/>

The John Day River, a tributary of the [[Columbia River]], flows generally north between the Mascall Formation Overlook and Kimberly, generally west from Kimberly to downstream of the unincorporated community of [[Twickenham, Oregon|Twickenham]], and generally north thereafter.<ref name="DeLorme"/> Rock Creek enters the river at the north end of Picture Gorge.<ref name="Rivers and Streams"/> [[Bridge Creek (John Day River)|Bridge Creek]] passes through Mitchell, then north along the eastern edge of the Painted Hills Unit to meet the John Day downstream of Twickenham.<ref name="Rivers and Streams">{{cite web|title=Rivers and Streams|publisher=National Park Service|date=August 23, 2006|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/rivers.htm|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> Intermittent streams in the Clarno Unit empty into Pine Creek, which flows just beyond the south edge of the unit and enters the John Day upstream of the unincorporated community of [[Clarno, Oregon|Clarno]].<ref name="DeLorme"/><ref name="Rivers and Streams"/>

== History ==

[[File:Clarno palisades 2.jpg|thumb|left|Palisades at the Clarno Unit of the monument]]
People have lived in Oregon for more than 10,000 years. Evidence suggests that [[Sahaptin people|Sahaptin]] groups such as the [[Warm Springs tribes|Warm Springs]], [[Umatilla tribe|Umatilla]] and [[Wasco-Wishram|Wasco]] inhabited the north-central part of the state. Surveys have found 36 sites of archeological interest, including rock shelters and [[cairn]]s, in or adjacent to the John Day Fossil Beds National Monument. Most significant among the prehistoric sites are the Picture Gorge [[pictogram|pictograph]]s, consisting of six panels of rock art in the canyon at the south end of the Sheep Rock Unit. By the 18th&nbsp;century, [[Paiute people|Northern Paiutes]] had also moved into the region from further south and lived in the upper John Day basin. All of these peoples were hunter-gatherers subsisting on local resources such as as [[salmon]], deer, [[elk]], [[Camassia quamash|camas]], and [[huckleberry|huckleberries]].<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 1">Beckham and Lentz, Ch. 1: "Indigenous Peoples and Cultures", pages not numbered.</ref>  

The John Day basin remained largely unexplored by non-natives until the mid-19th&nbsp;century. [[Lewis and Clark Expedition|Lewis and Clark]], who noted the John Day River while traveling along the Columbia River in 1805, did not ascend it. [[John Day (trapper)|John Day]], for whom the river is named, apparently visited only its confluence with the Columbia in 1812. In 1829, [[Peter Skene Ogden]], working for the [[Hudson Bay Company]] (HBC), led a company of explorers and fur trappers along the river through what would later become the Sheep Rock Unit. [[John Work]] of the HBC also visited this part of the river in 1831.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 2">Beckham and Lentz, Ch. 2, "Early Explorations and Expeditions", pages not numbered.</ref>   

In the 1840s, thousands of settlers began emigrating west over the [[Oregon Trail]]. Subsequent clashes between natives and non-natives and the desire of the U.S. Government to populate the region with Euro-Americans led to the gradual removal of native residents to [[Indian reservation|reservation]]s, including three in north-central Oregon: [[Warm Springs Indian Reservation|Warm Springs]], [[Burns Paiute Tribe|Burns Paiute]], and [[Umatilla Indian Reservation|Umatilla]].<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4">Beckham and Lentz, Ch. 4, "Settlement", pages not numbered.</ref> After passage of the [[Homestead Act]] of 1862 and the discovery of gold in the upper John Day basin, more non-natives moved to the region, established villages and engaged in subsistence farming and ranching near streams.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4"/>  Settlement was made more practical by a supply route from [[The Dalles, Oregon|The Dalles]] on the Columbia River to mines at [[Canyon City, Oregon|Canyon City]] in the upper John Day valley.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 5"/> By the late 1860s, the route became formalized as the The Dalles<U+2013>Boise Military Road, which passed along Bridge Creek and south of Sheep Rock.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 5">Beckham and Lentz, Ch. 5, "Transportation", pages not numbered.</ref>

[[File:Thomas condon of oregon.jpg|upright|thumb|right|[[Thomas Condon]]]]
In 1864, a company of soldiers sent to protect mining camps from raids by Northern Paiutes discovered fossils in the [[Crooked River (Oregon)|Crooked River]] region, south of the John Day basin. One of their leaders, Captain [[John M. Drake]], collected some of these fossils for [[Thomas Condon]], a missionary pastor and amateur geologist who lived in The Dalles.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4"/> Recognizing the scientific importance of the fossils, Condon accompanied soldiers traveling through the region, where he discovered rich fossil beds along Bridge Creek and near Sheep Rock in 1865. Condon's subsequent trips to the area and his public lectures and reports about his finds led to wide interest in the fossil beds among scientists such as [[Edward Drinker Cope]] of the [[Academy of Natural Sciences]] and paleontologist [[Othniel Charles Marsh|Othneil C. Marsh]] of [[Yale University|Yale]], who accompanied Condon on a trip to the region in 1871. Condon's work led to his appointment in 1872 as Oregon's first State Geologist and to international fame for the fossil beds. Specimens from the beds were sent to the [[Smithsonian Institution]] and other museums worldwide, and by 1900 more than 100 articles and books had been published about the John Day Fossil Beds. During the first half of the 20th&nbsp;century, scientists such as [[John C. Merriam]], Ralph Chaney, Frank H. Knowlton, and Alonzo W. Hancock continued work in the fossil beds, including those discovered near Clarno in about 1890.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 7">Beckham and Lentz, Ch. 7, "Paleontological Exploration", pages not numbered.</ref> 

Remote and arid, the John Day basin near the fossil beds slowly attracted homesteaders.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4"/> The first settler in what became the Sheep Rock Unit is thought to have been Frank Butler, who built a cabin along the river in 1877.<ref>McArthur, p. 131</ref> In 1881, Eli Casey Officer began grazing sheep on a homestead claim in same general area.<ref>{{cite web|title=History & Culture|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/historyculture/index.htm|publisher = National Park Service|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> His son Floyd later lived there with his family and sometimes accompanied Condon on his fossil hunts.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4"/> In 1910, James and Elizabeth Cant bought {{convert|700|acre|ha}} from the Officers<ref name="Places">{{cite web|title=Places|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/historyculture/places.htm|publisher = National Park Service|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> and converted it to a sheep ranch, which was eventually expanded to a sheep-and-cattle ranch of about {{convert|6000|acre|ha}}.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 4"/>

===Park creation===
The State of Oregon, recognizing a public interest in the fossil beds and encouraged by Merriam,<ref>{{cite web|last=Maguire|first=Kaitlin|title=John Day Fossil Beds National Monument, Oregon|url=http://www.ucmp.berkeley.edu/science/parks/johnday.php|publisher = University of California Museum of Paleontology|accessdate=July 16, 2011}}</ref> began in the early 1930s to buy land for state parks at Picture Gorge, the Painted Hills, and Clarno that later became part of the national monument.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 7"/> In 1951 the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] established Camp Hancock, a field school for young students of geology, paleontology, and other sciences, on public lands surrounded by what would later become the Clarno Unit.<ref name="Hard Places, Ch. 7"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Hancock Field Station|publisher = Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|url=http://www.omsi.edu/hancock-summercamps|http://www.omsi.edu/hancock-summercamps|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> After much planning and political debate, the national monument was established on October 8, 1975.<ref name="Administrative History, Ch. 3">Mark, Ch. 3, "Campaign for a National Monument", pages not numbered.</ref>

The [[James Cant Ranch Historic District]], {{convert|200|acre|ha}} that included the Cant Ranch House and nearby structures, was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1984.<ref name="registration form">{{cite web|last = Toothman|first=Stephanie|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Cant, James, Ranch Historic District|url=http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NRHP/Text/84003000.pdf|publisher= National Park Service|year= 1983|format=PDF|accessdate=July 16, 2011}}</ref> After the monument opened in 1975, the ranch house served as headquarters for all three units. In 2004, it also became home to the Cant Ranch Historical Museum, two rooms of public exhibits about the native cultures, the [[Canyon City, Oregon|Canyon City]] gold rush, ranching, and other topics related to region.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cant Ranch House Museum opens to the Public|publisher=National Park Service|location=John Day Fossil Beds National Monument|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/parknews/upload/newsletter04summerfall.pdf|format=PDF  |work=Park News: John Day Fossil Beds|date=Summer/Fall 2004|page=1|accessdate=July 17, 2011}}</ref> The Thomas Condon Paleontology Center, a $7.5&nbsp;million museum and visitor center at the Sheep Rock Unit, also opened in 1984.<ref name="living lab">{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Richard L.|title=A living lab for a fossil past|work=The Oregonian|publisher=Oregonian Publishing Co.|page=Sunrise C07|date=August 10, 2005}}</ref> Among the center's offerings are displays of fossils, murals depicting life in the basin during eight different periods ranging from about 45&nbsp;million to about 5&nbsp;million years ago, and real-time views of paleontologists at work.<ref name="living lab"/>

==Geology==

[[File:Joda geologic timeline.png|thumb|right|Timeline for major rock formations in the monument]] The John Day Fossil Beds National Monument lies within the Blue Mountains [[physiographic province]], which originated during the late [[Jurassic]] and early [[Cretaceous]], about 118 to 93&nbsp;million years ago.<ref>Bishop, p. 65</ref> Northeastern Oregon was assembled in large blocks (exotic [[terrane]]s) of [[Permian]], [[Triassic]], and [[Jurassic]] rock shifted by [[Tectonics|tectonic]] forces and [[Accretion (geology)|accreted]] to what was then the western edge of the North American continent, near the Idaho border.<ref>Orr, p. 21</ref> By the beginning of the [[Cenozoic]] era, 65&nbsp;million years ago, the Blue Mountains province was uplifting and eroding, and the Pacific Ocean shoreline, formerly near [[Idaho]], lay west of the new province.<ref>Orr, p. 29</ref>

Volcanic eruptions about 44 million years ago during the [[Eocene]] deposited lavas accompanied by mud flows ([[lahar]]s) atop the older rocks in the western part of the province. The mudflows of shales, [[siltstone]]s, conglomerates, and [[breccia]]s entombed plants and animals caught in their paths and later eroded into rock formations such as those exposed in the Clarno Unit.<ref>Orr, pp. 30, 46</ref> Preserved in the nut beds, palisades, and other formations of the unit are fossils of tropical and subtropical nuts, fruits, roots, branches, and seeds.<ref name="geology fieldnotes">{{cite web|title=Geology Fieldnotes|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nature.nps.gov/geology/parks/joda/#geology|accessdate=July 25, 2011}}</ref> Large animals inhabiting this region between 50 and 35 million years ago included [[Browsing (herbivory)|browser]]s such as [[brontothere]]s and [[amynodont]]s, scavengers like the [[Hyaenodontidae|hyaenodont]]s, as well as [[Patriofelis]] and other predators.<ref name="geology fieldnotes"/> Eroded remnants of the Clarno [[stratovolcano]]es, once the size of [[Mount Hood]], are still visible near the monument, for example Black Butte, White Butte, and other [[butte]]s near [[Mitchell, Oregon|Mitchell]].<ref>Bishop, 86<U+2013>92</ref> 

The Clarno volcanics subsided by the early [[Oligocene]] but were replaced about 36 million years ago by eruptions from volcanoes to the west, in the general vicinity of what much later became the [[Cascade Range]].<ref name="Orr 30-31"/> The John Day volcanoes, as they are called, emitted large volumes of ash and dust, much of which settled in the John Day basin. As with the earlier Clarno mudflows, the rapid deposition of ash preserved the remains of plants and animals living in the region. Because ash and other debris fell during varied climatic and volcanic conditions and accumulated from many eruptions extending into the early [[Miocene]] (about 20&nbsp;million years ago), the sediment layers in the fossil beds vary in their chemical composition and color.<ref name="Orr 30-31"/> Laid down on top of the Clarno Formation (from the Clarno volcanics), the John Day Formation (from the John Day volcanics) consists of several distinct groups of layers. The lowermost, the Big Basin member, consists of highly oxidized and deep red ash such as that exposed in the Painted Hills Unit and the nearby Bridge Creek Flora site, with its ''[[Metasequoia]]'' (dawn redwood) fossils.<ref>Orr, pp. 30<U+2013>31, 46</ref> The Turtle Cove member above it is mainly pea-green clay. Resting atop the Turtle Cove member are the buff-colored Kimberly and Haystack members.<ref name="Orr 30-31">Orr, pp. 30<U+2013>31</ref> Fossils found in the John Day Formation include a wide variety of plants and more than 100 kinds of mammals, including dogs, cats, swine, [[oreodont]]s, horses, camels, and rodents.<ref name="geology fieldnotes"/>  

After another period of erosion, a series of lava eruptions from fissures across northeastern Oregon, southeastern Washington, and western Idaho inundated much of the Blue Mountain province with liquid [[basalt]]. Extruded in the middle Miocene between 17 and 12&nbsp;million years ago, more than 40 separate flows contributing to the [[Columbia River Basalt Group]] have been identified, the largest of which involved up to {{convert|400|mi3|km3}} of lava. The most prominent of these formations within the monument is the Picture Gorge Basalt, which rests above the John Day Formation.<ref>Orr, p. 32</ref>

Subsequent ashfall from eruptions in the Cascade Range in the late Miocene contributed to the Mascall Formation, a layer of stream-deposited volcanic [[tuff]]s laid atop the Picture Gorge Basalt.<ref name="Orr 33">Orr, p. 33</ref> Preserved in the Mascall are fossils of horses, antelope, camels, bears, broadleaf plants, and other life forms that thrived in the monument's open woodland and savannah between 15 and 12&nbsp;million years ago.<ref name="geology fieldnotes"/><ref name="Orr 33"/> The last major eruption in the late Miocene deposited the Rattlesnake Formation, capped by an [[ignimbrite]], on top of the Mascall.<ref name="Orr 34">Orr, p. 34</ref> The Rattlesnake has fossils of [[mastodon]]s, camels, rhinoceroses, and others that grazed on the grasslands of the time.<ref name="geology fieldnotes"/><ref name="Orr 34"/>

===Fossils===

The monument contains extensive deposits of well-preserved fossils from various periods spanning more than 40&nbsp;million years.<ref name="Field Trip">{{cite book|last=Fremd|first=Theodore|coauthors=Bestland, Erick A.; Retallack, Gregory J.|title=John Day Basin Paleontology: Field Trip Guide and Road Log|year=1997|publisher=Northwest Interpretive Association|location=Seattle|pages= 11&ndash;13|ISBN=0-914019-40-6}}</ref> Taken as a whole, the fossils present an unusually detailed view of plants and animals since the late Eocene.<ref name="Reconstructions"/> Analysis of the John Day fossils has contributed to [[paleoclimatology]] (the study of Earth's past climates) and life-form [[evolution]].<ref name="Reconstructions">{{cite journal|author=Retallack|first=Gregory J.|coauthors=Bestland, Erick A.; Fremd, Theodore J.|title=Reconstructions of Eocene and Oligocene Plants and Animals of Central Oregon|work=Oregon Geology|url=http://www.oregongeology.org/pubs/OG/OGv58n03.pdf|publisher=Oregon Department of Geology and Mineral Industries|date=May 1996|volume=58|number=3|page=51|format=PDF|issn=0164-3304|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>

Paleontologists at the park find, describe the location of, and collect fossil-bearing rocks from more than 700 sites within the monument.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Day Fossil Beds Paleontology|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/john-day-fossil-beds-paleontology.htm|publisher=National Park Service|year=2006|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> They take them to the paleontology lab at the visitor center, where the fossils are stablized, separated from their rock matrix, and cleaned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fossil Laboratory|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/fossil-laboratory.htm|publisher=National Park Service|year=2006|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> The fossil specimens are then catalogued, indexed, and stored in climate-controlled cabinets for retrieval by researchers worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Collections|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/collections.htm|year=2006|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> In addition to preparing fossils, the paleontologists coordinate the monument's basic research in [[paleobotany]] and other scientific areas and manage the fossil museum in the visitor center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fossils|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/fossils.htm|year=2006|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>

==Climate==

Average precipitation, limited by the [[rain shadow]] effects of the Cascade Range and the Ochoco Mountains, varies from {{convert|9|to|16|in|mm}}.<ref name ="Nature and Science">{{cite web|title=Nature and Science|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/naturescience/index.htm|date=September 24, 2006|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> In winter, much of the precipitation arrives as snow.<ref name ="Nature and Science"/>

At Mitchell, near the Painted Hills Unit, July and August are the warmest months, with an average high of {{convert|86|F|C}} and an average low of {{convert|52|F|C}}.<ref name= "WeatherChannel"/> January is the coldest month, when highs average {{convert|42|F|C}} and lows average {{convert|24|F|C}}.<ref name= "WeatherChannel"/> The highest recorded temperature in Mitchell was {{convert|107|F|C}} in 1972, and the lowest was {{convert|-27|F|C}} in 1983.<ref name= "WeatherChannel"/> May is generally the wettest month, when precipitation averages {{convert|1.65|in|mm}}.<ref name= "WeatherChannel"/> 

