==Activities==

Entrance to the park and its visitor center, museums, and exhibits is free,<ref>{{cite web|title=Fees & Reservations|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/feesandreservations.htm|year=2006|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> and trails, overlooks, and picnic sites at all three units are open during daylight hours year-round.<ref name="Hours and seasons"/> No food, lodging, or fuel is available at the park, and camping is not allowed. However, lodging, groceries, gasoline, campsites, and other amenities are available elsewhere in the region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Campgrounds|publisher = National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/campgrounds.htm|year=2007|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> Except for the Cant Ranch, individual park buildings are open every day except Federal holidays between [[Thanksgiving]] (the fourth Thursday of November) and [[Washington's Birthday|Presidents Day]] (the third Monday of February). Operating hours for the main visitor center (Thomas Condon Paleontology Center) are from 9&nbsp;a.m. to 5&nbsp;p.m. Its amenities include a fossil museum, theater, education classroom, bookstore, restrooms, and drinking fountains.<ref name="Accessibility">{{cite web|title=Accessibility|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/accessibility.htm|year=2008|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> Hours of operation for Cant Ranch vary seasonally.<ref name="Hours and seasons">{{cite web|title = Operating Hours & Seasons|publisher = National Park Service |url =http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/hours.htm|year = 2011|accessdate = July 27, 2011}}</ref> The ranch house contains a cultural museum, restrooms, and a drinking fountain as well as park staff headquarters.<ref name="Accessibility"/>

The Sheep Rock Unit has eight trails ranging in length from {{convert|300|ft|m}} at the Mascall Formation Overlook to {{convert|3|mi|km}} at Blue Basin.<ref name="Sheep Rock Trails">{{cite web|title=Sheep Rock Trails|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/sheep-rock-trails.htm|publisher=National Park Service|year=2007|accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref> Four trails of a quarter-mile to {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} long cross parts of the Painted Hills Unit.<ref name="Painted Hills Trails">{{cite web|title=Trails at the Painted Hills|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/trails-at-the-painted-hills.htm|year=2006|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> At the Clarno Unit, three separate quarter-mile trails begin at a parking lot along Oregon Route 218, below the face of the Clarno Palisades.<ref name="Clarno Trails">{{cite web|title=Clarno Trails|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/clarno-trails.htm|publisher=National Park Service|year=2006|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> Many of the trails have interpretive signs about the history, geology, and fossils of the region, and three trails&mdash;Story in Stone at the Sheep Rock Unit, and Painted Cove and Leaf Hill at the Painted Hills Unit&mdash;are accessible by wheelchair.<ref name="Sheep Rock Trails"/><ref name="Painted Hills Trails"/><ref name="Clarno Trails"/>

Ranger-led events at the monument include indoor and outdoor talks, showings of an 18-minute orientation film, hikes in Blue Basin, Cant Ranch walking tours, and astronomy programs at the Painted Hills Unit. These events are free and do not require reservations. Specific times, which are variable, can be had from rangers at the monument.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indoor Activities|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/indooractivities.htm|year=2006|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ranger Guided Activities|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/ranger-guided-activities.htm|publisher=National Park Service|year=2011|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref>

Pets are allowed in developed areas and along hiking trails but must leashed or otherwise restrained. Horses are not allowed on the trails, in the picnic areas, or on bare rock exposures in undeveloped areas of the monument.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pets|publisher=National Park Service|year= 2006|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/pets.htm|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> Digging, disturbing, or collecting any of the park's natural resources, including fossils, is prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|title=Park Regulations|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/park-regulations.htm|year=2007|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> No mountain biking is allowed on monument land, although the [[Malheur National Forest]] east of Dayville has biking trails.<ref name="Outdoor Activities">{{cite web|title=Outdoor Activities|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/outdooractivities.htm|year=2006|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> Fishing is legal from monument lands along the John Day River for anyone with an Oregon fishing license. Rafting on the John Day River is seasonally popular, although the favored runs begin at or downstream of [[Service Creek, Oregon|Service Creek]] and do not pass through the monument.<ref name="Outdoor Activities"/> Risks to monument visitors include extremely hot summer temperatures and icy winter roads, two species of poisonous rattlesnakes, two species of poisonous spiders, [[tick]]s, scorpions, [[Tribulus terrestris|puncturevine]], and poison ivy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your Safety|publisher=National Park Service|year=2006|url=http://www.nps.gov/joda/planyourvisit/yoursafety.htm|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref>

